# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
If a word is a prefix of the string s, it means the string s starts with that word. The Java String class provides a method startsWith() that can be used to determine if a string starts with a certain prefix. We can use this method to simplify our solution.

# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
1. Initialize a Counter: Start by initializing a counter to zero. This will keep track of how many words from the array are prefixes of s.

2. Iterate Over the Words: Go through each word in the words array.

3. Check for Prefix: For each word, check if s starts with that word using the startsWith() method. If it does, increment the counter.

4. Return the Counter: After checking all the words, return the counter.

# Complexity
- Time complexity: O(n * m)
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
where n is the number of words and m is the average length of a word. This is because the startsWith() method compares characters of the word with the string s and, in the worst case, this can be O(m).

- Space complexity: O(1)
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
as we are using only a fixed amount of extra space (the counter) regardless of the size of the input.

