solutions.content:
In the first approach, we sort `potions`, and use binary search to find the position of the weakest potion that produces a success. All potions to the right would work also.

In the second approach, we sort both `potions` and `spells` (we actually sort indexes `idx` to preserve the order of spells). Then, we use two pointers to track the weakest  `potions[j]` that works for `spells[i]`. Since we process spells from weakest to the strongest, pointer `j` is moved in one direction - from strongest to weakest.

#### Binary Search
**C++**
```cpp
vector<int> successfulPairs(vector<int>& spells, vector<int>& potions, long long success) {
    sort(begin(potions), end(potions));
    for (int i = 0; i < spells.size(); ++i) {
        long long comp = (success + spells[i] - 1) / spells[i];
        spells[i] = potions.size() - (lower_bound(begin(potions), end(potions), comp) - begin(potions));
    }
    return spells;
}
```
#### Two Pointers
**C++**
```cpp
vector<int> successfulPairs(vector<int>& spells, vector<int>& potions, long long success) {
    vector<int> idx(spells.size());
    iota(begin(idx), end(idx), 0);
    sort(begin(potions), end(potions), greater<int>());
    sort(begin(idx), end(idx), [&](int i, int j){ return spells[i] < spells[j]; });
    for (int i = 0, j = 0; i < idx.size(); ++i) {
        while (j < potions.size() && (long long)potions[j] * spells[idx[i]] >= success)
            ++j;
        spells[idx[i]] = j;
    }
    return spells;
}
```

