# Intuition & Approach
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
In the question, we can see a basic pattern that we have to search a value for every element in spell. If we do this searching linearly for all n elements of spell (m times).

It will give us complexity of `O(n*m)`. This complexity can be reduced to  `O(n * logm)`  by using binary search. But before that we have to sort the array potions.
```C++ []
sort(potions.begin(), potions.end());   // sorting array of potions
```

Now, it is given in the question that we have to find the number of elements in potions that multiply with spell[i] to give value >= success.

In simple words: 
$$spells[i] * potions[j]  >=  success$$

Taking spells[i] on R.H.S. we get:
$$potions[j] >= success / spells[i]$$

So minimum possible value of potion for spells[i] is `success / spells[i]`. Now, it is clear that we have to find **$$lower bound$$** in our already sorted array of potions. And we know,  all the elements after this lower bound in the potions array will be greater (as the array is sorted in increasing order), so we will get the answer by doing m - lower bound.
```
ans[i] = m - lower_bound_ind;
```
Please check the code below.



