solutions.content:
# Intuition:
A brute force would've been easy but the constraints don't let us.

We just need the number of elements in `potions` which when multiplied by a particular number (from `spells`) gives the value greater than or equal to `success`.

So if we sort the array `potions`, we can apply a binary search to reach the starting index in `potions` from where onwards all the products yield value >= `success`.

The number of elements that yields product >= `success` is equal to:
`length of potions - starting index`

---

# Code:
```
class Solution {
    public int[] successfulPairs(int[] spells, int[] potions, long success) {
        int n = spells.length, m = potions.length;
        Arrays.sort(potions);
        int[] pairs = new int[n];
        for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
            int startIdx = findStartIndex(spells[i], potions, success);
            pairs[i] = m - startIdx;
        }
        return pairs;
    }

    private int findStartIndex(int spell, int[] potions, long success) {
        int m = potions.length;
        int lo = 0, hi = m - 1;
        // Initialise the start index as the length of potions array
        // because there might be a case when all the potion strengths
        // when multiplied by spell strength gave a less product value than success
        // so when we do potions.length - startIdx, it will automatically become 0
        // because start index will never get updated to a lesser value (mid)
        int startIdx = m;
        while (lo <= hi) {
            int mid = lo + (hi - lo) / 2;
            long prod = 1L * spell * potions[mid];
            // if product is >= success
            if (prod >= success) {
                // save this potential start index
                startIdx = mid;
                // look for a lesser potion strength
                hi = mid - 1;
            } else {
                // product was too less
                // go for a greater potion strength
                lo = mid + 1;
            }
        }
        return startIdx;
    }
}
```
---
