solutions.content:
This is a standard dynamic programming question.

Use max[m, n] where max[m, n] is the maximum money you can earn from cutting an m x n piece of wood.

**Base cases** in this question are found in prices array.

For the **recurrence relation**, we check all horizontal/vertical cut for each piece, m x n. Then we pick the largest price from the optimal subpieces. We use bottom-up dp to ensure that subpiecess are optimal before moving on to the larger pieces.

max[m, n] = **Maximum of**:
		**horizontal**: { max[i][n] + max[m-i][n] } for all 1 <= i < m
	    **vertical**:   { max[m][j] + max[m][n-j] } for all 1 <= j < m

Edge cases. It is possible that a single 2x2 might cost less than four 1x1 pieces.
Therefore, you should check each and every piece from 1x1. 

```
class Solution {
    public long sellingWood(int m, int n, int[][] prices) {
        long[][] dp = new long[m+1][n+1];
        for (int[] price : prices) {
            dp[price[0]][price[1]] = price[2];
        }
        for (int i = 1; i < m+1; i++) {
            for (int j = 1; j < n+1; j++) {
                // all horizontal
                for (int k = 1; k <= i/2; k++) {
                    dp[i][j] = Math.max(dp[i][j], dp[i-k][j] + dp[k][j]);
                }
                // all vertical
                for (int k = 1; k <= j/2; k++) {
                    dp[i][j] = Math.max(dp[i][j], dp[i][j-k] + dp[i][k]);
                }
            }
        }

        return dp[m][n];
    }
}
```
**Time complexity** = O(mn(m+n))
Check for each piece = O(mn)
For each piece, check all cuts = O(m+n)

**Space Complexity** = O(mn)

