solutions.content:
**Observation 1:**
Ex- _ L _ R _ _ R _ L
Look at the example and imagine _ moving . We will notice that _ pushes L to left and it pushes R to right.

We can remove all the spaces and store the new string in s(start string without _ ) and t(target string without _ ), if s!=t the answer is false as L and R cannot cross each other so there's no way to make start==target.

**Observation 2:**
_ will move L only towards left, so if the index of L in start is lesser than L in target, then it is not possible to make the strings equal.
So in a vector(l1) we store all the indexes where start[i]='L' and in another vector(l2) we store all the indexes where target[i]=='L'. Then we loop the vector and if at any index l1[i]<l2[i] we return false.

**Observation 3:**
Similarly, _ will move R only towards right, so if the index of R in start is greater than R in target, then it is not possible to make the strings equal.
So in a vector(r1) we store all the indexes where start[i]='R' and in another vector(r2) we store all the indexes where target[i]=='R'. Then we loop the vector and if at any index r1[i]>r2[i] we return false.

