solutions.content:
We can think of L's and R's as two types of brackets. For example,
```
_L__R__R_
L______RR
```
is equivalent to
```
_)__[__[_
(______]]
```
We can use two counters to keep track of opening brackets and make sure that
1.  Brackets of difference types don't intersect, i.e. we can't have opening brackets of difference types at the same time.
2.  A closing bracket must be paired with an opening bracket.
3.  No opening brackets remain in the end.
```
class Solution {
public:
    bool canChange(string s, string t) {
        int l = 0, r = 0, n = s.size();
        for (int i = 0; i < n; ++i) {
            l += t[i] == 'L';
            r += s[i] == 'R';
            if (r && l) return false;
            l -= s[i] == 'L';
            r -= t[i] == 'R';
            if (r < 0 || l < 0) return false;
        }
        return l == 0 && r == 0;
    }
};
```

