solutions.content:
You don't need a DS or complex nested loops for this.

Since the combinations are limited, we will have 3 simple cases where it will fail to match.

When we get an L, **increment** if it's in **start** and **decrement** if it's in **target**.
Likewise do the same for R.

At every step check these **3 cases** and **`return false`** if any of them satisfy.

**Cases :**
```
L > 0 || R < 0
start[i] == 'L' && R > 0
start[i] == 'R' && L < 0
```
**`Note : The following code can be easily converted into c++ as well as there are no Data structures used.`**

**Solution :** 
```
    public boolean canChange(String start, String target) {
        int n = start.length();
        int L = 0, R = 0;

        for(int i=0;i<n;i++){
            if(L > 0 || R < 0)
                return false;

            char a = start.charAt(i);
            char b = target.charAt(i);

            if(a == 'L'){
                if(R > 0)
                    return false;
                L++;
            }
            if(a == 'R'){
                if(L < 0)
                    return false;    
                R++;
            }

            if(b == 'L')
                L--;
            if(b == 'R')
                R--;
        }

        return L == 0 && R == 0;
    }
```

