solutions.content:
# Intuition
First properly understand the question. 
It says that **we need to count the subarrays filled with 0's.**
Questions in your head can be:
- Can we consider other numbers in the array?
 No. We cannot. The description clearly says: **return the number of subarrays filled with 0.** And the subarray is **a contiguous non-empty sequence of elements**.

So, we can clearly see that our subarray will only contain **0**'s and they need to be contiguous.

Now let's think of an example. Let's say we are given:
```
nums = [0]
```
Our answer will be 1. As we have count of 0 = 1.
If for example:
```
nums = [0, 0]
```
Our answer will be 3.
**How?**

![image.png](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/b4a7fe58-3b26-40d1-8c21-cb4de5ee0e69_1679376615.5399365.png)

If the example was:

```
nums = [0, 0, 0]
```

![image.png](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/6dda2e7f-1c35-4028-bfaa-8b4d2a171b44_1679376800.4900432.png)

So, far we have shown only the zeroes. Now suppose for a real example.
For Example 2:

```
nums = [0,0,0,2,0,0]
```
![image.png](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/1af7768e-7cdf-404a-bcd4-b10fc9cfb431_1679377165.6141438.png)


<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->

# Approach

Keep a variable named `contCount` that stores the continuous count of 0s. Initially it will be 0. When we encounter an element 0, we increment it.
When we encounter an element other than 0, we reset variable contCount to 0. But before that we need to calculate the subarrays found from it.
We can see a pattern from above examples.
For two continuous zeroes:
The contCount will be 3.
So, the subarrays will be `3 + 2 + 1 = 3 * (3+1)/2 = 6`.
Remember the Gauss formula you learned in Math class?
$$
n* \frac{(n+1)}{2}
$$
So, this way we can calculate the subarrays.

**But there's a modification that can improve this efficiency. Discussed below.**
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->

# Complexity
- Time complexity: O(N)
Iterating only once
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

- Space complexity: O(1)
No new array, vector, map, list declaration! Only constant 2 variables.
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

# 34% Efficiency:
``` Java []
class Solution {
    public long zeroFilledSubarray(int[] nums) {
        long contCount = 0;
        long subarrays = 0;
        for(int i=0; i<nums.length; i++){
            if(nums[i]==0){
                contCount++;
            }
            else{
                subarrays += (contCount*(contCount+1)/2);
                contCount=0;
            }
        }
        // if the last element was 0, we need to calculate for it
        if(contCount>0){
            subarrays += (contCount*(contCount+1)/2);
        }
        return subarrays;
    }
}
```
