# Intuition
Find the number of **consecutive zeroes** in the array and add **n*n(+1)/2 **in the running sum, where is n is the number of consecutive zeroes in some part of the array.

# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
We are finding the pattern in this problem.
For example, `{1,2,0,0,0,5}` In this array, we have 3 consecutive ones.
Number of time 0 appear 3 times = 1
Number of time 0 appear 2 times = 2
Number of time 0 appear 1 times = 3
Total = 1 + 2 + 3 = 6
which is nothing but 3*(3+1)/2.
In general, `n*(n+1)/2`, where n is the number of consecutive zeroes.
Thus, we iterate over the array and add thereby add the result in the running sum.
At last return the sum.


# Complexity
- Time complexity: O(n)
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

- Space complexity: O(1)
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

# Code
```
class Solution {
    public long zeroFilledSubarray(int[] nums) {
        long ans = 0;
        long zer = 0;
        int i = 0;
        int n = nums.length;
        while(i<n){
            if(nums[i]!=0){
                ans += zer*(zer+1)/2;
                zer = 0;
            }else{
                zer++;
            }
            i++;
        }
        ans += zer*(zer+1)/2;
        return ans;
    }
}
