# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
To find the number of subarrays filled with 0 in an array, we need to count the number of subarrays ending at each index that are filled with 0. For example, in the array [1, 0, 0, 2, 0, 3, 0], there are 4 subarrays ending at index 2 that are filled with 0: [0], [0, 0], [1, 0, 0], and [0, 0, 2, 0, 0]. Therefore, the total number of subarrays filled with 0 in the array is the sum of the number of subarrays filled with 0 ending at each index.

# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
We can use a simple approach to count the number of subarrays filled with 0. We iterate over the array and keep track of the count of consecutive zeros seen so far. Whenever we encounter a non-zero element, we reset the count to 0. For each zero encountered, we increment the count and add it to the answer. This works because the count represents the number of subarrays ending at the current position that are filled with 0.

# Complexity
- Time complexity:
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
 The time complexity of this approach is $$O(n)$$, where n is the length of the array. This is because we iterate over the array once.
- Space complexity:
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
The space complexity of this approach is $$O(1)$$, because we only use a constant amount of extra space to store the count and answer.



