# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
Using Math formula n*(n+1)/2 to calculate the number of possible sub-arrays of zeros within a given sub-array of zeros.

 #### *Please upvote if u like the solution..

# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
Find a possible continuous sub-array of zeros. If it's length is 'm' then the number of possible sub-arrays withing that sub-array of zeros can be calculated by the summation formula m*(m+1)/2

# Complexity
- Time complexity:
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
O(n) as we need to iterate over the array once.

- Space complexity:
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
O(1) as we do not use any extra memory that grows with input size.

# Code
```
public class Solution {
    public long ZeroFilledSubarray(int[] nums) {
        long count = 0;
        long result = 0;
        for (int i = 0; i < nums.Length; i++)
        {
            if (nums[i] == 0)
                count++;
            else if (count > 0)
            {
                result += (count * (count + 1)) / 2;
                count = 0;
            }
        }

        if (count > 0)
        {
            result += (count * (count + 1)) / 2;
        }

        return result;
    }
}
```

