Intuition: 
See the problem different from how its explained. Take this subarray `0, 0, 0, 0`. From this there will be <br>
Size 1  -> 4 subarrays -> [1 to 1] [2 to 2] [3 to 3] [4 to 4]
Size 2  -> 3 subarrays -> [1 to 2] [2 to 3] [3 to 4]
Size 3  -> 2 subarrays -> [1 to 3] [2 to 4]
Size 4  -> 1 subarray  ->  [1 to 4]
So the sum of all the subarrays would be `4 + 3 + 2 + 1`. From this you can see that, if a subarray is of size `n`, the number of subarrays generated from that would be sum of 1 to n, which we can get by `S(n) = (n * (n + 1)) / 2 `

