**Intuition:**
Total number of subset in a array of size n is found using n*(n+1)/2
So if we find all the sub-arrays containing only 0 then we can apply out formula and
the final answer would be the sum of all the sub array count 

```
class Solution {

    public long zeroFilledSubarray(int[] nums) {

        // find range of all the subsets of 0
        HashMap<Integer, Integer> map  = new HashMap<>();
        long ssCnt = 0L;
        int i = 0, n = nums.length;

        while(i < n){
            if(nums[i] != 0){
                i++;
                continue;
            };

            int j = i;
            while(j+1 < n){
                if(nums[j+1] == 0){
                    j++;
                }else{
                    break;
                }
            }

            map.put(i, (j-i+1));

            i = j+1;
        }

        for (Integer r : map.values()) {
            Long R = 1L * r;
            long temp = 1L* (R*(R+1))/2;
            ssCnt += temp;
        }

        return ssCnt;
    }
}
```

