# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
Store the length of the total number of continuos occurrence of 0 in the array and store it into a List.
and just iterate over the List and apply the formula =  (N * (N+1)) / 2;
to each element of the List and whatever output will get from that formula add it to the final answer

# Complexity
- Time complexity: O(n)
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

- Space complexity: O(n)
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

# Code
```
class Solution {
    public long zeroFilledSubarray(int[] nums) {
        int i = 0;
        long count = 0;
        ArrayList<Long> al = new ArrayList<>();
        while(i != nums.length){
            //if nums[i] == 0 increase the count
            if(nums[i] == 0){
                count++;
                i++;
                continue;
            }
            //if nums[i] != 0 then store the count in the array and 
            //re-initialize the count to 0
            else{
                //check if the count is 0 no need to store un-neccssary
                if(count != 0){
                    al.add(count);
                }
                count = 0;
            }
            i++;
        }
        //checking for the last element of the array if its 0 then store the count
        if(nums[nums.length-1] == 0){
            al.add(count);
        }
        long ans = 0;
        for(Long num : al){
            ans += (num*(num+1))/2;
        }
        return ans;
    }
}
```
Note : 
The formula for calculating the sum of all natural numbers from 1 to N is:

Sum = (N * (N+1)) / 2

In other words, the sum of the first N natural numbers is equal to half the product of N and N+1.

